Even his longest periods are seldom tinged with obscurity of expression. More often, perhaps, it is his very conciseness of utterance, with undue importance attaching to a single word or phrase, that causes his reader to pause and reflect upon the full signifi- canee of a statement. But Suetonius himself never tarries for calm judgment and accurate weighing of the evidence he pre- sents.
